Introduction¶

In this report I would be looking at a data which reports patient who showed up for their scheduled appointment or not. The data set records the appointment date, scheduled date, gender, patient id, Age, neighbourhood.

The dependent variable, 'No-show' consist of 'yes' or 'No' values corresponding to when a scheduled appointment was missed or when a scheduled appointment was honored respectively.

My research questions are:

  1. Are certain age groups more prone to missing their appointment than others?
  2. Does gender influence appointments no shows?
  3. What neighbourhoods has the highest paercentage of no shows?
  4. On what day of the week are patients most likely to miss their appointment?

def add_datepart(df, fldname):
    """
    This function adds the year, month, week, and day of week to a dataframe.
    df= name of dataframe
    fldname
    """
    fld = df[fldname]
    targ_pre = re.sub('[Dd]ates','', fldname)
    for n in ("Year", "Month", "Dayofweek",):
        df[targ_pre+n] = getattr(fld.dt, n.lower())
    return df

Note¶

This function will enable the creation of a day of the week column to be used in answering Question 4

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In [79]:
# Creating a function to allow creation of percentage grouping per feature against the dependent variable 'No-show'.
# This is because different amounts of observation per category per feature are sampled, thus a simple count of observation
#   will be misleading but a ratio of show to no-show for each category in a feature gives an objective comparission basis.
# rather that Percentage was used as it is a more visually pleasing metric than ratio.

def pct_group_df(df, groupby_col, agg_col): 
    """
    This function returns a dataframe that have been grouped and aggregated by [ercentage a parameter existing in the dataframe
    df= dataframe to be used to create new subset of the dataframe
    groupby_col= column to group by
    agg_col= aggregate column    
    """
    
    
    df1= df.groupby(groupby_col)[agg_col].value_counts(normalize=True).mul(100).rename('Percentage(%)')
    df2= pd.DataFrame(df1).reset_index()
    df2.rename({'level_1': agg_col}, axis=1, inplace=True)
    return df2
In [80]:
# Creating a plot function to enable easy plotting

def plot_bar(df, y_axis, x_axis, z_axis=None, title='title', NoShow=None, plotsize=None, color=None):
    """
    This function returns a Bar plot of a dataframe
    df= dataframe to be used in plot
    y_axis= string of relevant column name to be used in as Y-axis of the plot
    x_axis= string of relevant column name to be used in as X-axis of the plot
    z_axis= string of relevant column name to be used as a third variable in the plot
    title= title to be used as the plot title
    NoShow= Default None. Yes subsets the 
    """
    
    
    fig, axes= plt.subplots(figsize= plotsize)
    
    if NoShow== None:
        df_use= df
    else:
        df_use= df[df['No-show']== NoShow]
    
    sns.barplot(x= x_axis, y= y_axis, hue=z_axis, data= df_use, ci=False, color=color)
    plt.ylabel(y_axis)
    plt.title(title)
    
    return plt.tight_layout()

Conclusions¶

Observations;¶

Accoss all predictors variables investigated, Age groups, Neighbourhood, and day of week all vary alond with noshow across their categories except for Gender which showed to be neutral.

Age Groups: Form the above we see that Youth have the highest percentage of highest percentage of no-shows per appointment, while Adults have the least percentage of appointment no-show accross all observations.

Neighbourhood: Neighbourhoods with the highest amount of appointment no-shows are shown above with Ihas Oceanicas de Trindade not recording any patient from the neighbouhood showing up for an appointment, while Parque Industrial has the best record of appointment show up, with all patients showing up.

Day of Week: From the plots above, Saturdays have the highest percentage scheduled appointment no shows, while wednesday has the least percentage of appointment no-show.

Gender: Appoximately thesame ratio of males and females miss their scheduled appointments, thus Gender does not affect appointment no-shows

Constriants:¶

  1. The predictor features are geared towards the adult to elderly and does no necessarily accomodate an inclusive population across all age groups. Therefore information on walkin cases would have provided a much fairer basis to compare the population.
  1. The distance of the neghbourhoods from the hospital would have given better insights as to determing the kind of relationship between the dependent variable and neighbourhood.
